This completes the proof that the product of inner products is integrable.

Now we can proceed to the main inequality. In Lean, this would involve showing that the `L^p` norm of the sum is bounded by the constant times the `L^(p/2)` norm of the sum of squared norms. This would typically involve using the properties of the norm and inner product, and applying the appropriate inequality (often Cauchy-Schwarz, or more directly using properties of symmetric random variables).

